A CALL TO ACTION"Action without vision is only passing time, vision without action is merely day dreaming, but vision with action can change the world!" ~ Nelson Mandela   "Rewilding The Lost Wilderness: Green Heritage of the Forgotten Cape" is an epic literary masterpiece of South African cultural history, heritage and conservation! 

The Impact: to distribute books free of charge to schools and libraries in rural, previously disadvantaged communities.

The Cause: to conserve the history of wildlife and conservation in South Africa.
The Mission: to inspire and facilitate rewilding and restitution of wilderness throughout South Africa for the benefit of wildlife and previously disadvantaged communities. 
THE IMPACT    In keeping with the vision of Madiba, the Father of the South African nation, "Rewilding The Lost Wilderness: Green Heritage of the Forgotten Cape" was written to inspire change and action through the uniting force of conservation.   Through the combined efforts of the "Rewilding The Lost Wilderness: Green Heritage of the Forgotten Cape" team, we aim to: 
Distribute books free of charge to rural community libraries and schools - thereby conserving the multi-cultural heritage of and for all South Africans;
Inspire unity and economic upliftment among previously disadvantaged communities through the expansion of "rewilding areas" and game reserves;
Inspire the creation of community operated game reserves - through free "Rewilding The Lost Wilderness" consultancy to previously disadvantaged communities;
Inspire the continued conservation of the globally threatened species, which sadly includes both the local black and white rhinoceros;
Serve as a guideline for the restitution of wilderness areas across South Africa, and;
Serve as an example for global rewilding initiatives. 
THE CAUSE   "Rewilding The Lost Wilderness: Green Heritage of the Forgotten Cape" is a tale of the unknown Africa! A wilderness forgotten in the midst of colonization, urbanization, and exploitation! But a lost wilderness that has proven resilient and a forgotten wilderness with hope!    The North American prairie has its bison, the European tundra has its reindeer and the Central Asian steppe has its saiga antelope, but nowhere else on this globe is there a greater spectacle of wildlife and wilderness than in Africa! No other continent can boast with the immense diversity and expansive wilderness.   Yet along the southernmost extremities of the continent lies a land with a much different reality. Here the ancient rhythm of Africa has been disturbed, changed and distorted! Endless herds of gazelle, wildebeest and half-striped zebra have been replaced with far-ranging mutton estates. Raucous parrots and their evergreen forests retreated into far off districts and inaccessible mountain slopes. Lagoons and river mouths where the hippopotamus and crocodile openly bathed in the morning sun gave way to harbours, towns and cities. Rolling coastal hills and mountain slopes where the leopard found his favorite haunt now stands adorned with some of the finest vineyards and olive groves in the southern hemisphere! Where vast grasslands with bontebok and blue antelope once ranged across the Overberg panorama, now only wheat and canola fields flourish. And even the mighty Clanwilliam cedar tree nearly went the way of the dodo, as its fragrant wood was sculpted into lavish furniture! This transformed part of southern Africa came to be known as the Cape! Today this region is defined as the three south-westernmost provinces of South Africa, and not half of its story has been told!   After more than 350 years of European settlement much about the former wilderness has been forgotten, and for many the notion of lions, rhinos and elephants in Cape Town might come with a strong sense of disbelief. But the Dutch colonization was by no means the beginning of the story of man’s wandering in these southern districts, for the exploits of man in the Cape goes back many centuries! First came the Stone Age hunter-gatherers with power over the element of fire! On the heels of the San followed the Stone Age Khoikhoi pastoralists with their herds of sheep, goats and cattle. As the Khoikhoi spread across the entire face of the Cape, the Iron Age dawned with the arrival of the Bantu-speaking Nguni and later Tswana farmers. By 1488 European forays to these shores commenced as Portuguese seafarers set foot on South African soil! And after Dutch colonization in the year 1652 the Cape was never to be the same again!   However, the real Africa is a land of innovation, optimism and restoration! After much environmental and socio-political unrest, as various cultures surpassed their predecessors and came to define their own borders within this multi-cultural blend, the Cape was left in a state of wildlife neutrality! Vast Karoo plains devoid of springbok, blesbok, black wildebeest and quagga; Fynbos laden mountains devoid of red hartebeest, eland and elephant; and water courses devoid of hippopotamus. But the modern African was not satisfied to have African bush devoid of African wildlife, and so we embark on the quest to ‘rewild’ this forgotten wilderness!   "Rewilding The Lost Wilderness: Green Heritage of the Forgotten Cape" is the story of a quintessential African wilderness that has been lost and is being regained! It is a story of hope and restoration! A tale of hope for all the wilderness areas that has been lost, and an example for all wilderness areas that is still to be regained!~ Marcel H. van der Merwe"a South African author, conservation activist, and philanthropist."THE MISSION       "I read Marcel van der Merwe’s book with great interest and empathy, his authors note really says it all and he is to be complimented on producing an outstanding contribution to conservation literature. Sixty two years of my life has now been spent in the battle for the conservation of wildlife and wilderness in South Africa, also in other countries such as the Philippine Islands where I assisted in the preservation of the tamaraw, a diminutive buffalo on the island of Mindoro.   The Cape Province has always been of great interest to me although I have never lived there. I always remember my great friend, Colonel Sir Laurens van der Post CBE, giving speeches and talking about the history of the Cape and how the hippo came out into Table Bay to welcome the first settlers and how the black rhino existed on the top of Table Mountain. He had a way of touching the hearts of the audiences that he spoke to. The wild animals and the Bushmen were always part of his story. The wild landscapes of his early youth were deeply ingrained on his psyche. His ability to describe wild landscapes, wild animals and wild people, always left a deep impression. It is no wonder that his Royal Highness Prince Charles came to regard Laurens van der Post as a mentor.   I believe Marcel van der Merwe’s book deserves the thanks not only of South Africans, but people in other countries who increasingly are becoming concerned about the plight of wild animals and wild country in South Africa. The current slaughter of white and black rhino, animals that I have been closely associated with and done my best to protect, is very much in the forefront of the great struggle to conserve our wildlife. The birth of wildlife sanctuaries such as Shamwari and Sanbona, created through the genius and hard work of Adrian Gardiner in the Eastern Cape have proved that wildlife conservation has been a tremendous boon, not only to the conservation of animals, but also to the tourist industry which I believe will eventually prove its critical importance to South Africa because it is sustainable, unlike the minerals which will eventually run out. Adrian Gardiner’s efforts have now been emulated in other parts of the Cape and are proving again not only important for wildlife, but also economics.   The earliest game ranches in South Africa originated in the Cape with the saving of the bontebok and we can be grateful that Adrian Gardiner and others have carried on that tradition. It is my hope that Marcel van der Merwe’s book will inspire other landowners to recreate wild lands for the protection of all wildlife; animals, birds, vegetation and landscapes. His book is a mine of valuable information, a most important resource for present and future conservationists wanting to restore the wild lands of our country."~ Dr. Ian Player"(born March 15, 1927) a South African environmental educator, conservationist, sportsman and activist."WHAT WE NEED     In order to make this South African heritage and conservation masterpiece a reality we need funds to cover the final production costs. The bulk of which includes community outreach orientated expenses, and some professional and artistic layout fees and costs regarding final printing.   In order to achieve positive impact in the local, previously disadvantaged communities of South Africa we initially need around $50,000 to facilitate:
The free distribution of books to schools and libraries in rural and previously disadvantaged communities, especially in the Western Cape, Eastern Cape (birthplace of Nelson Mandela) and Northern Cape of South Africa.
The general logistics of community outreach (especially in rural parts of the Cape like the Transkei).
The provision of free consultancy to communities concerning the development of ecological friendly and economically sustainable community owned game reserves, and the logistics involved in such an operation.
"Only after the last tree has been cut down, only after the last river has been poisoned, only after the last fish has been caught. only then will you find - that money cannot be eaten" ~ Chief Seattle
